ing to Japanese Americans in the aftermath of their wartime confinement, including resettlement nationwide, the mental and physical readjustment of the former inmates, and their political engagement, most notably in concert with other racialized and ethnic minority groups.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2020) 0aCold WarxSocial aspectsxUnited States. 0aCold WarxSocial aspectszUnited States. 0aCommunity lifexHistoryx20th centuryxUnited States. 0aCommunity lifezUnited StatesxHistoryy20th century. 0aJapanese AmericansxCivil rightsxHistoryx20th century. 0aJapanese AmericansxCivil rightsxHistoryy20th century. 0aJapanese AmericansxEvacuation and relocation, 1942-1945. 0aJapanese AmericansxPolitics and governmentx20th century. 0aJapanese AmericansxPolitics and governmenty20th century. 0aJapanese AmericansxSocial conditionsx20th century. 0aJapanese AmericansxSocial conditionsy20th century. 7aHISTORY / United States / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUC Press eBook Package 2000-2015z978311066334108iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUC Press eBook Package Backlist 2000-2013z978311069042240uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520952270423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780520952270.jpg  a978-3-11-066334-1  UC Press eBook Package 2000-2015c2000d2015  a978-3-11-069042-2  UC Press eBook Package Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_FAO  aGBV-deGruyter-alles